**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- `enableDefaultTyping()` allows attackers to specify arbitrary classes to instantiate
- Jackson will create objects of attacker-controlled types during deserialization
- Gadget chains like JdbcRowSetImpl can trigger JNDI lookups to attacker servers
- Combined with JNDI injection, this leads to remote code execution
- Many "gadget" classes exist in common libraries (C3P0, Commons Collections, etc.)

