**Key Security Controls**:
- **Private module paths**: Use your organization's domain (git.mycompany.com) to prevent public registry hijacking
- **Explicit version pinning**: Lock to specific versions, not `latest` or ranges
- **Checksum verification**: `go.sum` file validates package integrity - commit this file
- **GOPRIVATE configuration**: Tell Go which modules are private to skip public proxy

Excellent concern! Vulnerable dependencies are one of the most exploited attack vectors. The Drupalgeddon2 vulnerability (CVE-2018-7600) affected over 1 million sites and allowed complete server takeover through an outdated Drupal core. Similar issues regularly affect PHP packages via Composer.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```php
<?php
// composer.json with outdated and vulnerable dependencies
// This is a typical legacy project with frozen dependencies

/*
{
    "name": "mycompany/legacy-app",
    "require": {
        "php": ">=7.2",
        "laravel/framework": "5.5.*",
        "guzzlehttp/guzzle": "6.3.0",
        "phpmailer/phpmailer": "5.2.21",
        "symfony/http-foundation": "3.4.0",
        "league/flysystem": "1.0.0"
    }
}
*/

// Dangerous: Using outdated PHPMailer with RCE vulnerability
require_once 'vendor/autoload.php';

use PHPMailer\PHPMailer\PHPMailer;

class ContactController
{
    public function sendEmail($request)
    {
        $mail = new PHPMailer();

        // Vulnerable: PHPMailer 5.2.21 has CVE-2016-10033
        // Allows RCE through crafted sender address
        $mail->setFrom($request['email'], $request['name']);
        $mail->addAddress('contact@company.com');
        $mail->Subject = $request['subject'];
        $mail->Body = $request['message'];

        // No validation, attacker can inject shell commands
        $mail->send();

        return ['status' => 'sent'];
    }
}
```

**Attack Payload** (CVE-2016-10033):
```text
"attacker\" -oQ/tmp/ -X/var/www/html/shell.php some\"@email.com
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- PHPMailer 5.2.21 contains CVE-2016-10033 allowing Remote Code Execution
- Guzzle 6.3.0 has multiple security issues including SSRF vulnerabilities
- Laravel 5.5 is end-of-life with no security patches since 2020
- Dependencies are pinned to exact versions, preventing automatic security patches
- No dependency scanning or audit process in place

**SECURE VERSION**:

```php
<?php
// composer.json with secure dependency management
/*
{
    "name": "mycompany/secure-app",
    "require": {
        "php": "^8.1",
        "laravel/framework": "^10.0",
        "guzzlehttp/guzzle": "^7.8",
        "phpmailer/phpmailer": "^6.9",
        "symfony/http-foundation": "^6.4",
        "league/flysystem": "^3.23"
    },
    "require-dev": {
        "roave/security-advisories": "dev-latest",
        "enlightn/security-checker": "^2.0"
    },
    "scripts": {
        "security-check": "security-checker security:check",
        "post-install-cmd": [
            "@security-check"
        ],
        "post-update-cmd": [
            "@security-check"
        ]
    },
    "config": {
        "audit": {
            "abandoned": "fail"
        }
    }
}
*/

namespace App\Http\Controllers;

use PHPMailer\PHPMailer\PHPMailer;
use PHPMailer\PHPMailer\Exception;
use Illuminate\Http\Request;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Log;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Validator;

class SecureContactController extends Controller
{
    public function sendEmail(Request $request)
    {
        // Validate and sanitize all inputs
        $validated = Validator::make($request->all(), [
            'email' => 'required|email:rfc,dns|max:255',
            'name' => 'required|string|max:100|regex:/^[a-zA-Z\s]+$/',
            'subject' => 'required|string|max:200',
            'message' => 'required|string|max:5000'
        ])->validate();

        try {
            $mail = new PHPMailer(true);

            // Use SMTP instead of mail() to avoid injection
            $mail->isSMTP();
            $mail->Host = config('mail.mailers.smtp.host');
            $mail->SMTPAuth = true;
            $mail->Username = config('mail.mailers.smtp.username');
            $mail->Password = config('mail.mailers.smtp.password');
            $mail->SMTPSecure = PHPMailer::ENCRYPTION_STARTTLS;
            $mail->Port = config('mail.mailers.smtp.port');

            // Safe: Using validated, sanitized inputs
            $mail->setFrom(config('mail.from.address'), config('mail.from.name'));
            $mail->addReplyTo($validated['email'], $validated['name']);
            $mail->addAddress('contact@company.com');
            $mail->Subject = htmlspecialchars($validated['subject'], ENT_QUOTES, 'UTF-8');
            $mail->Body = htmlspecialchars($validated['message'], ENT_QUOTES, 'UTF-8');

            $mail->send();

            Log::info('Contact email sent', [
                'from' => $validated['email'],
                'ip' => $request->ip()
            ]);

            return response()->json(['status' => 'sent']);

        } catch (Exception $e) {
            Log::error('Email send failed', [
                'error' => $e->getMessage(),
                'ip' => $request->ip()
            ]);
            return response()->json(['status' => 'error'], 500);
        }
    }
}
```

**Key Security Controls**:
- **Semantic versioning with caret (^)**: Allows automatic minor/patch updates including security fixes
- **roave/security-advisories**: Blocks installation of packages with known vulnerabilities
- **Input validation**: Strict validation before any processing
- **SMTP transport**: Avoids mail() function injection vectors entirely

